---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Breadcrumbs from '../../components/Breadcrumbs.astro';
import PageHero from '../../components/PageHero.astro';
import Faq from '../../components/Faq.astro';
import References from '../../components/References.astro';
import LinkCard from '../../components/LinkCard.astro';
import GetMatchedCta from '../../components/GetMatchedCta.astro';

const path = '/spokane/adu-rules-spokane-county';
const title = 'ADUs in Unincorporated Spokane County';
const description =
  'ADU rules for unincorporated Spokane County: the urban growth area split under HB 1337, the role of Title 14 zoning and Building and Planning, and how to confirm your parcel.';

const faqItems = [
  {
    q: 'How do I know if my lot is in unincorporated Spokane County?',
    a: 'If your parcel is not inside any city, the unincorporated Spokane County rules apply. Cities within the county, including Spokane, Spokane Valley, Cheney, Liberty Lake, and Airway Heights, have their own codes. Identify your jurisdiction first, because the rules differ.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Does HB 1337 apply in unincorporated Spokane County?',
    a: 'It applies to the urban growth area (UGA) portions of the county, where two ADUs per lot and no owner-occupancy requirement apply under HB 1337. Outside the UGA, the county sets its own standards. So the first question for a county lot is whether it is inside the UGA.',
  },
  {
    q: 'What are the Spokane County BP-75 and BP-76 sheets?',
    a: 'BP-75 (detached) and BP-76 (attached) are Spokane County Building and Planning information sheets for ADUs. They are a helpful starting point, but the controlling source is the county zoning code (Title 14) and the Building and Planning department, not the brochure.',
  },
];
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description} path={path}>
  <Breadcrumbs items={[{ label: 'Spokane rules', href: '/spokane' }, { label: 'Unincorporated Spokane County', href: path }]} />
  <PageHero
    eyebrow="Jurisdiction"
    title="ADUs in Unincorporated Spokane County"
    lede="These rules apply to parcels in unincorporated Spokane County, meaning lots not inside any city. The key questions are your parcel's zone and whether it sits inside an urban growth area, because HB 1337 applies inside the urban growth area but the county sets its own standards outside it."
    cta={{ href: '/get-matched', label: 'Get matched with a builder' }}
    secondary={{ href: '/guides/can-i-build-an-adu-spokane', label: 'Can I build an ADU?' }}
  />

  <section class="container-prose rich-text pb-2">
    <h2>Identify your jurisdiction first</h2>
    <p>
      Spokane County contains several incorporated cities, including Spokane, Spokane Valley, Cheney,
      Liberty Lake, and Airway Heights. Each writes its own ADU rules. The guidance here applies only
      to unincorporated county land.
    </p>

    <h2>How unincorporated county ADU rules work</h2>
    <p>
      Unincorporated Spokane County regulates ADUs through its zoning code (Title 14) and the Building
      and Planning department. The rules depend on your parcel's zone and whether it sits inside the
      urban growth area.
    </p>
    <p>
      Inside the urban growth area, Washington's HB 1337 requires the county to allow at least two
      ADUs per lot, with no owner-occupancy requirement and impact fees capped at 50 percent of the
      principal unit. Where the local code has not yet caught up to state law, state law controls.
    </p>
    <p>
      Outside the urban growth area, the county sets its own standards for size, height, setbacks, and
      parking, and some zones may require a conditional use permit. A separate state law, HB 1345,
      lets counties choose whether to allow a detached ADU on rural parcels.
    </p>
    <p>
      Because the exact requirements depend on your specific parcel, confirm the current standards
      with Spokane County Building and Planning before you design or apply.
    </p>

    <h2>Septic and water</h2>
    <p>
      Many county lots use a septic system and sometimes a private well rather than municipal sewer
      and water. Septic capacity can be a deciding feasibility factor for a county ADU and is reviewed
      by the Spokane Regional Health District, with water service confirmed through the serving
      purveyor. It is worth checking early.
    </p>

    <h2>The permit process in the county</h2>
    <p>
      ADU permits for unincorporated parcels run through Spokane County Building and Planning. To
      confirm the current rules for your specific lot, including its urban growth area status, use the
      county zoning code or contact the county Permit Center at 509.477.3675. Our homeowner permit
      guide explains what to expect.
    </p>
  </section>

  <Faq items={faqItems} heading="Unincorporated Spokane County ADU questions" />

  <References
    sources={[
      { label: 'Spokane County Codes and Ordinances, Zoning Code Title 14 (spokanecounty.gov)', href: 'https://www.spokanecounty.gov/720/Codes-Ordinances', note: 'The controlling ADU source for unincorporated county land.' },
      { label: 'Spokane County BP-75, Detached ADU (spokanecounty.gov)', href: 'https://www.spokanecounty.gov/DocumentCenter/View/682', note: 'Orientation sheet, not the controlling source.' },
      { label: 'Spokane County BP-76, Attached ADU (spokanecounty.gov)', href: 'https://www.spokanecounty.gov/DocumentCenter/View/683', note: 'Orientation sheet, not the controlling source.' },
      { label: 'RCW 36.70A.680 and .681 (app.leg.wa.gov)', href: 'https://app.leg.wa.gov/RCW/default.aspx?cite=36.70A.681', note: 'HB 1337 and its urban growth area applicability.' },
    ]}
  />

  <section class="container-page py-8">
    <h2 class="font-serif text-2xl font-semibold">Related</h2>
    <div class="mt-6 grid gap-5 sm:grid-cols-3">
      <LinkCard href="/guides/adu-permits-spokane" eyebrow="Guide" title="ADU Permits in Spokane" blurb="The homeowner walkthrough of the permit process." />
      <LinkCard href="/guides/adu-cost-spokane" eyebrow="Guide" title="ADU Cost in Spokane" blurb="Dated cost ranges with basis." />
      <LinkCard href="/guides/hb-1337-spokane" eyebrow="Guide" title="HB 1337 Explained" blurb="Why the UGA split matters." />
    </div>
  </section>

  <GetMatchedCta />
</BaseLayout>
